article.headline: Raptors overcome McGrady's huge fourth quarter

images.name: Carter_Vince 021603 inline
images.caption: Vince Carter scored 12 points for the Raptors.

article.linkText: T-Mac fails to lift Magic out of road slump
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Vince Carter believes the Toronto Raptors can make the playoffs no matter how improbable the odds are. Alvin Williams had 22 points, Antonio Davis scored 21 and the Raptors won for the sixth time in eight games Sunday with a 99-97 victory over the Orlando Magic. "It's always been believable for me. We have to believe it now. We've put ourselves in a tough situation, but it's not a farfetched dream,'' said Carter, whose team improved to 16-35, the second-worst record in the Eastern Conference. The Raptors are 6-2 since Carter returned to the lineup after missing 23 consecutive games with an injured right knee. They would need to win 25 of their remaining 31 games to reach .500. Tracy McGrady scored 14 of his 36 points in the fourth quarter for the Magic, who went 0-3 on their three-game road trip. After McGrady's 3-pointer cut Toronto's lead to 99-97 with 31 seconds left, Toronto's Morris Peterson missed a 3-pointer. The Magic had a chance to tie or go for the win with 8 seconds left, but Mike Miller didn't get his 3-point attempt off before the buzzer. "I was looking for the ball and it didn't get to me,'' McGrady said. "You just have to find your playmaker in situations like that.'' Carter added 12 points for the Raptors, who shot 52 percent from the field compared to 41 percent for the Magic. Carter's 3-pointer gave Toronto a 90-78 lead with 4:25 left, but McGrady's three-point play, Pat Garrity's 3-pointer and McGrady's free throw cut Toronto's lead to six with 2:21 left. Williams followed with two free throws, but McGrady made a dunk. Davis made two free throws before McGrady's jumper and Jacque Vaughn's 3-pointer cut Toronto's lead to three with a 1:00 left. Carter then tipped in his own miss, but McGrady followed with his 3-pointer to cut the lead to two with 31 seconds remaining. After Peterson missed his 3-pointer, the Magic could have called a 20-second timeout, but Darrell Armstrong ran the ball up the court. "He should have turned around and given it to Tracy,'' Orlando coach Doc Rivers said. "The one thing you have to do is find the best player in the league and get him the ball.'' McGrady, booed every time he touched the ball, also had 12 rebounds and eight assists. He has scored at least 30 points in 12 of his last 14 games. The Magic, down by 15 at halftime, closed within five with a 14-4 run to start the second half. Peterson had five points and Davis had four as the Raptors followed with a 9-2 run to take a 66-54 lead. "We lost the game in the first half,'' Garrity said. Davis and Williams each had 12 points as the Raptors led 53-38 at halftime. Williams had six points during a 10-2 run late in the second quarter. His jumper with 40 seconds left in the half gave Toronto a 15-point lead -- the Raptors' biggest of the game. "Vince usually carries the load, but I think the team has been doing a great job with different people stepping up,'' Williams said. Game notes
The Raptors will attempt to fly to Washington for Monday's game against the Wizards despite the severe snowstorm in Washington. ... The Magic have lost five straight road games. ... Actress Susan Sarandon sat courtside. Sarandon also attended a Maple Leafs game on Saturday night. ... Orlando's Shawn Kemp had five points and three rebounds in his first game since being suspended for violating the league's anti-drug program. ...
